#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:136
# 486cc56e58214afab0df1b806c2e9df1
msgid "4.2 Set Minimum Outside Air Intake Correctly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:138
# 9dce5ccad3474f2ca89cc5142c4e249e
msgid "Outside air intake rates are often significantly higher than design values in existing buildings due to lack of accurate measurement, incorrect design calculation and balancing, and operation and maintenance problems. Excessive outside air intake isoften directly caused by one or more of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:140
# f4a8c57b4e5a4808800249eea49af40e
msgid "Mixed air chamber pressure is lower than the design value. For example, the static pressure often varies from –0.2 in. H2O to –1.0 in. H2O when the design assumed –0.1 in. H2O or higher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:143
# f244d69e6f9341df851ce2f82795bf8f
msgid "Significant outside air leakage through the maximum outside air damper on systems with an economizer. Due to the large size of this damper, the air leakage can be significant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:146
# 0fb213575b154faf95179949247a6c39
msgid "Minimum outside air intake is set using minimum total air flow for a VAV system. For most existing systems, the minimum outside air damper position is set at a fixed position. When the total air flow is higher than the minimum system flow, the pressure in the mixed air chamber becomes more negative. Consequently, the outside air intake is higher than the minimum required when total air flow is higher than the minimum air flow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:152
# 0f00aee2d7224699808ea08944ca5e9b
msgid "Lower than expected/designed occupancy. For example, the outside air intake is often determined based on space peak occupancy schedule. However, when a meeting is held in a conference room, several offices are not occupied. It is estimated that 10% or more of the occupants will not be present in their working place at any given time due to travel, meetings, vacations or sick leave. Hence the minimum outside air flow is often significantly over- designed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:160
# 8aac97fa269f45bdb07b4714872f40d8
msgid "The excessive outside air intake consumes a significant amount of extra heating and cooling energy. Each extra cfm of outside air intake typically costs from $1 to $3 per year depending on location and energy cost. If there is too much outside air, the AHU may lose the ability to control room humidity and temperature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:162
# c630da8a9a464822aae61eb59e9a66b5
msgid "Excessive outside air intake can be identified by one of the following methods:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:164
# 2303d22e573c44ce85c771fa595df7f4
msgid "Measure CO2 level of the return air for critical zones. For a typical office building under normal occupied conditions, the return air CO2 level should be 500 ppm to 600 ppm higher than the outside air CO2 level when minimum design outside air is used. If the CO2 level of return air increases by less than 500 ppm under normal occupancy, it indicates excessive outside air intake. Do not apply this criterion during economizer cycle operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:170
# 562659fcdbd8474db0ae51e2aa942227
msgid "Measure outside air intake and compare with the design value. If a section of straight ductwork carries the outside air, a direct flow measurement is recommended. The airflow measurement may also be performed using turbine flow sensors in the inlet of the outside air intake grilles. However, this measurement should be performed when wind speed is lower than 15 FPM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:175
# e3ef4b89dc0043a6ad94cca46951c7c2
msgid "Measure air flow indirectly using temperature measurements. In most cases, the outside air intake goes directly or almost directly into the mixing chamber. Therefore, outside air flow is determined using measured total air flow and temperatures (mixed, outside and return):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:180
# d60aa3b51df94a37a473e0d7164ab4bf
msgid "CFM_{oa} = CFM_t\\frac{T_m - T_r}{T_{oa} - T_r}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/Chapter4.rst:185
# f39e0f4734724eb58af4119c5abf8540
msgid "This method can be used only when the temperature difference between return and outside air is greater than 10°F. To improve the measurement accuracy, one probe should be used to measure all temperatures. Be cautious about using control system sensors for these measurements. The typical measurement errors of control sensors are +1.5°F, which will, in many cases, significantly lower the accuracy of the outside air flow determined. The location of the sensors may also cause problems. The return air temperature sensor must be located on the discharge side of the return air fan. The mixed air temperature sensor must be located before the supply air fan. The temperature measurement methods must ensure true average temperature."
msgstr ""

